SECTION 4: MUON LIFETIME AS READING DIFFERENCE
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  A muon at rest decays in 2.197 μs. A muon at 0.99c
  decays in ~15.6 μs (as measured by a stationary observer).
  This is 'time dilation.' In DATA-5: the muon's internal
  process rate is FIXED. The observer measures it across
  a velocity boundary, which distorts the reading.

  v/c                 γ  τ_rest (μs)   τ_obs (μs)        Ratio
  ---------- ---------- ------------ ------------ ------------
  0.0               1.0        2.197        2.197          1.0
  0.5            1.1547        2.197       2.5369       1.1547
  0.9            2.2942        2.197       5.0402       2.2942
  0.99           7.0888        2.197       15.574       7.0888
  0.999          22.366        2.197       49.138       22.366

  The muon does NOT 'live longer.' Its internal process rate
  is UNCHANGED. The observer's measurement of its lifetime
  is distorted by the velocity boundary between the muon's
  reference frame and the observer's reference frame.

  The distortion factor γ = 1/√(1 - v²/c²) is the READING
  CORRECTION for observations across velocity boundaries.
  It is analogous to the (1 - GM/(rc²)) correction for
  observations across gravitational potential boundaries.
  [PASS] Muon at 0.99c: observed lifetime ~ 7× rest lifetime
        γ = 7.089

